JOHANNESBURG - Sundays are synonymous with thousands of Christians gathering in churches. The coronavirus pandemic is forcing believers to rethink the way they worship, so as not to bring large numbers of people together. WATCH: Ramaphosa meets religious leaders amid COVID-19 Sandton Assemblies of God chairman, John Ngcebetsha said, "we have had to adapt our methodology so we don't go against the laws of the country, but also that we don't fail in our mandate as a spiritual body."
While some believers choose to stay at home and stream their church service online, in Sandton, members of the Assemblies of God have to book their seat before setting foot inside their church. One member of the church, Percy Ingle said, "I am happy. I think our church did the best and is trying to do the best because we don't want to expose our members to this problem. At the same time, we are here to worship God and we not going to stop." READ: SA Council of Churches to meet over COVID-19 concerns In Alexandra, churchgoers are also worshipping in smaller groups. The Alexandra Assemblies of God pastor, Thami Mavimbela said, "we made a point of putting sanitisers at our points of entry and we have been doing a headcount and made sure there are only 100 chairs. " Essentially in these abnormal times, loving your neighbour means keeping your distance. Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs